Two methylthio groups are alkylthio substituents which moderately increase the melting point due to increased molecular weight and van der Waals forces; each might add around +30 degrees Celsius. Since there are two methylthio groups, their combined effect would be approximately +60 degrees Celsius. However, as electron donors, the methylthio groups may partially counteract the strong intermolecular interactions from the nitro group, slightly decreasing their additive effect. Therefore, a conservative estimate of their combined effect might be slightly lower, at about +50 degrees Celsius. Consequently, the overall estimated melting point of the compound would be the sum of the effects of these substitutions to the melting point of ethylene.
Prediction: -169.2 (ethylene base) + 180 (nitro group) + 50 (two methylthio groups) = 60.8 degrees Celsius
